Here is an example of how to create a simple search bar using PHP:

**index.php**
```php
<?php
// Connect to the database
$servername = "localhost";
$username = "username";
$password = "password";
$dbname = "database_name";

$conn = new mysqli($servername, $username, $password, $dbname);

if ($conn->connect_error) {
    die("Connection failed: " . $conn->connect_error);
}

// Check if the search query is set
if (isset($_GET['search'])) {
    $searchQuery = $_GET['search'];
} else {
    $searchQuery = "";
}

// Prepare and execute the SQL query to get the results
$sql = "SELECT * FROM table_name WHERE column_name LIKE '%$searchQuery%' LIMIT 10";
$result = $conn->query($sql);

// Display the search results
?>
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Search Results</title>
    <style>
        /* Add some basic styling to make it look nice */
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }

        #search-bar {
            width: 50%;
            height: 30px;
            padding: 10px;
            font-size: 16px;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Search Bar Example</h1>
    <form action="<?php echo $_SERVER['PHP_SELF']; ?>" method="get">
        <input type="search" id="search-bar" name="search" placeholder="Search...">
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>

    <?php
    if ($result->num_rows > 0) {
        // Output data of each row
        while($row = $result->fetch_assoc()) {
            echo "<p>" . $row["column_name"] . "</p>";
        }
    } else {
        echo "No results found";
    }

    $conn->close();
    ?>
</body>
</html>
```
**Explanation**

This example uses PHP to connect to a MySQL database and execute an SQL query based on the search query entered by the user.

Here's how it works:

1. The `index.php` file checks if the `search` GET parameter is set. If it is, it sets the `$searchQuery` variable with the value of the `search` parameter.
2. It then prepares and executes an SQL query to retrieve rows from a table where a specified column matches the search query. The query uses the `LIKE` operator with wildcards (`%`) to match any characters before or after the search term.
3. If the query returns results, it loops through each row using a `while` loop and displays the values of each column in an `<p>` tag.
4. Finally, it closes the database connection.

**Note**: This is just a basic example to demonstrate how to create a search bar using PHP. In a real-world scenario, you would want to use prepared statements to prevent SQL injection attacks, as well as handle errors and edge cases more robustly.

Also, make sure to replace `username`, `password`, `database_name` with your actual database credentials and table/column names.

